Right-wing populists win in Austria with 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both sides of the previous large coalition and a significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties led to early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People’s Party (ÖVP) has suffered severe losses, where the position of current president Wilhelm Molterer is seriously shaken.
On the other hand, the elected leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Korutan lieutenant Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but loses 5.5 percent against the last election in 2006.
Even worse was the result of the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these big parties in the Austrian post-war history, and especially among the people who caused early elections, a literally catastrophic outcome.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People’s Party had a significant advance over the SPÖ in preferences.
Voters, however, have clearly punished them for letting the government fail.
In the early reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party’s chairman and former deputy chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers estimate that this could happen on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party’s presidency.
Such a development would apparently facilitate the way to the ever more likely outcome from the election outcome, i.e. to the resumption of a large coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties – the Free Party (FPÖ) gained 18 percent and the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes – however, the Social Democrats also expressed concerns about the repetition of 1999, when the People’s Party agreed with the populists (then the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) on a joint government, which even triggered sanctions by the European Union.
On this development obviously bets Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and presupposes a return to Vienna to national politics.
In the parliament, the Greens lost slightly, falling from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties clearly crossed the four-percent threshold and did not enter parliament.
