Turkish diplomacy expands
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers sought to penetrate deep into the Turkish border.
On the eastern shore of the Bosphorus, only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a neorenaissance style.
The tour guide will tell you.
The building sits obkročmo at the end of the perimeter with a tower at each corner of the façade, in sight not to be distinguished from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly collapsing.
But once one gets into the curved box, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gateway the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium of the Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which joined the game of empires late, intended to realize its ambition to dominate the Middle East using this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their courses were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial troops advanced from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And bad news came for Hydarpaša station as well.
In 1917, an explosion of a ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then, it has gradually evolved and history has gone by.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves – at least symbolically – to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is being implemented – Turkey is engaging.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I took a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I had to meet with one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning — about ten and a half hours later — after a curly ride on the rails that reminded me of the ancient rhythms of the well-known Night Mail document, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, proposed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back to its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigms of Turkish consensus.
It has aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP main tent, an ultramodern stone and metal building, deliberately built on an emerging suburb, surrounded by semi-dispersed malls and power stores, where middle managers in business dresses – both men and women – meet to make early morning deals.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
The jacket, the tie, I’m sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The goal of the party’s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he told me.
Turkey was cut off from its territory.
We must look both east and west at the same time.
It was no choice.
He had to do both.
“But there will be a time,” I asked, “when will Turkey have to make a decision?”
“Turkey,” he said, “did not want such a decision to take place.”
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke with said almost in memory: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea surroundings are equally beneficial to Europe and the United States as well as to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go along these rails east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpaša station, after another overnight, I thought of the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched how this building was built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be if they found out that European ambitions in the Middle East could now be, in substantial part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited in the harbour for a ferry back over the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called “the sick man of Europe.”
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt which continent would be entitled to this fascinating country.
