“Auto bee” prevents collisions
To advance in the development of accidents-protecting technologies, Nissan is this time inspired by nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the model of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Center for Technical Progress of Nissan Motor Co. developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, chief public relations officer for brand technology, research and development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of Nissan’s security shield.
The robot is designed to enhance the ability to prevent collisions in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual function, the engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to a distance of two meters in a radius of 180 degrees ahead of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
“Once an obstacle is detected, the robot imitates bee movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all of the maneuvering is absolutely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
A robot, unlike a bee, cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited only to two dimensions and the direction that is allowed by the rotation of its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in a bee.
In addition to acceleration and slowing, Nissan also used the rotating function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process information every couple of seconds and maintain itself according to this data.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuition from previous manoeuvres, thanks to which it can operate without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
You may be surprised, but in memory, we’re not talking about giga or mega.”
This is the first step in the development of new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit in the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
