Rafael Correa on Monday in Quito.
To re-establish the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Eva Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correy.
Last Sunday, the third nominee submitted to the vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, a draft of a new Constitution.
And his mission is fulfilled, as 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the votes, voted "yes" in the referendum.
According to the results, 28% of the votes were "No", 7% were void and 0.7% were empty.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the votes plus one.
Two polls conducted on the east of the polls and a count of NGOs predicted a clear “yes” victory on Sunday, putting them in the range of 63 percent to 70 percent.
Rafael Correa claimed the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday.
“The Constitution has won on all lines,” he assured and congratulated the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It is obvious that Rafael Correa received congratulations from Chavez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), took place quietly, concerned the text of 444 points building the “new socialism” promoted by the president.
The draft constitution sanctifies the power of the state over the economy by reserving it the “development planning” of a country that lives primarily from foreign companies’ oil mining and foreign currencies sent by its emigrants.
The proposal, backed by Correa, which was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, which will be able to exercise two consecutive four-year terms and will have the option to dissolve the house.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and will run for a new mandate in February 2009.
The constitution, among other things, reinforces the principle of free healthcare and education, which the president began to introduce in a country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also counts on a ban on the presence of foreign troops, thus ending the agreement between Washington and Quito to use the Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. drug operations.
