Egyptian forces have captured 11 tourists and their eight-member escort who were abducted 10 days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were transported alive and healthy to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
In the morning they were liberated in Chad by the Egyptian command.
The hostages arrived around 15:30, apparently in good shape, on board a special aircraft to the al-Maza military base, adjacent to the international airport in Cairo.
They were immediately transported, without having the opportunity to comment in the press, on board a helicopter to a hospital in Maadi, the marginal residential district of Cairo, to undergo medical examinations there.
"They are completely healthy" and "no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoeyr Garrana said.
Since being captured on September 19 during a safari in a four-wheel drive vehicle at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the border of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group includes 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border officer, director of Aegyptous, the safari organizer.
A senior Egyptian security official indicated that 30 members of the special forces, who approached the site on board two helicopters, ran off during the night just before dawn.
“There was a shooting, half of the kidnappers were killed and the others fled,” said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He indicated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces from the Lightning unit were sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini from Belgrade, where he is now, mentioned the role played by secret agents and Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the people of our intelligence services, of the special forces," he said.
He also denied that the ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the attack, the Sudanese army said it had arrested a four-wheel-drive vehicle on board which had the kidnappers, killing six of them, including the Chadian commander, and arresting two.
The army claimed to be linked to the Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement - Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately rejected.
