Benelux State Part of Bank Fortis
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the spreading effect of the U.S. mortgage market crisis, by partially nationalizing: the three countries will support the money and insurance institute, which also has capital participation in Hungary, in the amount of 11.2 billion euros.
This was agreed at the highest level this weekend by the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first bank in the euro area to enter a major crisis as a result of the crisis in the international financial markets, which has spread in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made in this regard could in some respects be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision, the three states will buy back half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets.
The bank is sure to sell a portion of its equity stakes, especially the insurance activities it bought last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis stock began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week serious signs of crisis appeared in the constitution.
But analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to go bankrupt.
The company’s securities fell 12 percent on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the share price has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given current stock prices, the group’s total market capital value is around €14 billion, but according to the company’s executives, this is unrealistic.
The company’s management blames the fall in Fortis’ shares for overseas uncertainty related to the adoption of a $700 billion U.S. plan.
The shares rose slightly on Monday.
On Friday, the new CEO of the bank, Filip Dierckx, was appointed.
The bank was also looking for a private buyer, but no one has made a more serious offer so far.
The Belgian government has already said that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
There has been no panic among the bank’s clients, and branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also acquired several leasing companies.
A fox in a chicken
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people’s data on drug purchases, often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with an applicant.
Data protection experts are concerned that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken to a fox," said Richard Dick, the author of the drug prescription monitoring program.
Insurance companies make insurance premiums and amounts paid in case of insurance events dependent on the health status of the applicants, and if the risk is assessed as too great, they will not even conclude insurance with it.
Previously, they sent those concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: on the basis of an identification number, a pharmacy customer can easily find out what medicines the person concerned has bought in the past year and a half, from which the program itself deduces what he suffers from the disease and what his health status is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this indicates that he has virtually uncontrollably high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in the higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so the insurance company has almost no work left in addition to paperwork, although there are minor difficulties.
The disadvantages include that any medicines can be used for several purposes, some compounds are, for example, applicable against migraines or heat outbreaks, but are also effective against depression.
These represent a significant risk-increasing factor from the perspective of commercial insurance companies, whereas the first difficulties are not.
For the purpose of collecting and processing data, special companies have been created, which before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, will ask the patient for permission.
They are now forced to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their previous negligence.
Some companies have already processed the results of laboratory tests, which they combine with data on the medicines used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a special law on health data protection, but its effectiveness applies only to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to also control companies specializing in data provision, is in front of Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his program so that the transfer of data is subject to the express consent of the person concerned.
The other thing is that he can hardly deny permission, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
The chickens are somewhat dependent on the goodwill of the fox.
