The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying over the desert in Nevada, were found.
The debris was discovered at an altitude of 3,000 meters in the Mammoth Lakes area in Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
There were no human remains inside the plane.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispeled doubts that still remained: "The plane was found, we sent a team there and now we are sure it's exactly where Steve Fossett flew on the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old has been considered dead since February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said hours after the debris was detected, an investigative team was sent to identify the aircraft: it was exactly the Bellanc 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal items were found by one couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with Fossett’s name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, about cash and one coat.
The search for Fossett was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
